abstract = {Historically, the U.S. was the first country to formally introduce regulations that require a management system to safeguard processing plants following a series of chemical release incidents having catastrophic consequences. The issuing regulatory entity, Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) enforces the regulations for Process Safety Management (PSM) of facilities handling highly hazardous chemicals. This management system contains 14 elements that are to be incorporated over a covered facility's lifecycle. Other countries followed with similar management system requirements for process safety. Digitalization of the process industry is evident in nearly every system of chemical manufacturing. Digital controls and data communications as applied to processing plants continue to grow in capability as well as complexity. Advances in digital technologies have also affected the way PSM systems are applied to these facilities. While digitalization used in the PSM elements offers significant advantages with respect to effectiveness and efficiency, there are also disadvantages. These will be described for some of the elements in this chapter, along with a few practical applications. At the chapter's end, a few recent journal articles that have been briefly reviewed are summarized. These articles discuss future advanced safety management aspects, e.g., emphasizing the importance of digital twin technique for safe human-machine interaction, and how digitalization will support improvements in process safety by means of many different mechanisms.}
